I&#39;ll use `Supplier` from the standard library for this example. Let&#39;s say you have method with such signature:
```
static &lt;T&gt; T getSupplierResult(Supplier&lt;T&gt; supplier) {
  return supplier.get();
}
```
Naturally the supplier you provide can&#39;t throw exceptions. Now you need a functional interface declared to throw exceptions.
```
@FunctionalInterface
interface ThrowingSupplier&lt;T&gt; {

  T get() throws Exception;
}
```
Then you have to transform this throwing supplier into the standard one. With a method it will look like this:
```
static &lt;T&gt; Supplier&lt;T&gt; wrapThrowingSupplierAsSupplier(ThrowingSupplier&lt;T&gt; throwingSupplier) {
  return () -&gt; {
    try {
      return throwingSupplier.get();
    } catch (Exception e) {
      throw new RuntimeException(e);
    }
  };
}
```
Note that this method returns `Supplier&lt;T&gt;`, **not** `T`.

If you are not used to used to lambdas, the same can be achieved with a standard class:
```
private static final class ThrowingSupplierWrapper&lt;T&gt; implements Supplier&lt;T&gt; {

  private final ThrowingSupplier&lt;T&gt; throwingSupplier;

  ThrowingSupplierWrapper(ThrowingSupplier&lt;T&gt; throwingSupplier) {
    this.throwingSupplier = throwingSupplier;
  }

  @Override
  public T get() {
    try {
      return throwingSupplier.get();
    } catch (Exception exc) {
      throw new RuntimeException(exc);
    }
  }
}
```
And the invocations of the method which requires `Supplier`:
```
getSupplierResult(wrapThrowingSupplierAsSupplier(() -&gt; new FileInputStream(&quot;qwerty&quot;)));
getSupplierResult(wrapThrowingSupplierAsSupplier(() -&gt; new FileInputStream(&quot;faceroll&quot;)));
```
Or using the class:
```
getSupplierResult(new ThrowingSupplierWrapper&lt;&gt;(() -&gt; new FileInputStream(&quot;asd&quot;)));
```

